<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/standards-organization%20governance"=20
      rel=3Dtag>standards-organization governance</A></DIV>
      <P></P>
      <P>I am <EM>not</EM> tracking every little move that happens in =
March 2008=20
      as we determine whether or not the edited-per-the-BRM DIS 29500 =
will=20
      advance to an ISO/IEC IS 29500 and promulgation as an =
international=20
      standard.&nbsp; I have other work to do and other things to blog=20
      about.&nbsp; I shall return to my normal erratic mingling of =
topics.&nbsp;=20
      I promise.</P>
      <OL>
        <OL>
          <OL>
            <LI><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#1.0h">What's=20
            It All About?</A>=20
            <LI><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#2.0h">The=20
            US Score So Far</A>=20
            <LI><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#3.0h">"Who=20
            Are Those Guys?"</A>=20
            <LI><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#4.0h">Yes,=20
            but WHO Are Those Guys?</A><BR>4.1 <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#4.1h">Not=20
            Voting</A><BR>4.2 <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#4.2h">Abstention</A><BR>4.3=20
            <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#4.3h">The=20
            Loyal Opposition</A><BR>4.4 <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#4.4h">Friends=20
            Across the Aisle</A>=20
            <LI><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#5.0h">Eagerly-Anticipated=20
            Maintenance?</A></LI></OL></OL></OL>
      <H3><A name=3D1.0h>1</A>. What's It All About?</H3>
      <P>I'm posting this article because of two interesting =
factors:</P>
      <OL>
        <LI><STRONG>OOXML Maintenance might arise at ISO/IEC JTC1 Either =

        Way<BR></STRONG>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR>There is <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#5.0h">some=20
        interest</A> in the US National Body for immediately creating a =
new JTC1=20
        SC34 work item using an accelerated timeframe.&nbsp; The new =
project=20
        would produce an OOXML that has the BRM-recommended changes and =
also=20
        resolve more deliberatively all other BRM technical comments and =

        more.&nbsp; This would be a new OOXML specification (revising IS =
29500=20
        if there is one of those).<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR>The =
projected work=20
        is a little different depending on whether the edited DIS 29500 =
is=20
        approved or not.&nbsp; There's a suggestion that it could take 9 =
months=20
        to two years, depending on the situation and the quality of the =
edited=20
        DIS 29500.&nbsp; <STRIKE>I have not found the relevant JTC1 =
procedures=20
        to understand what these accelerated timeframe processes=20
        are.</STRIKE>&nbsp; I <STRIKE>also</STRIKE> have no statistics =
on the=20
        degree of under-estimation that happens with "accelerated =
timeframe"=20
        projects, <U>although there is apparently strong oversight =
(section <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#5.0h">5</A>)</U>.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <BR>I raise this here as something to keep our eye =
on.&nbsp;&nbsp; We=20
        have the prospect of a moving target for a few more years.&nbsp; =
The=20
        legacy solution may require legacy handling.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>What's the US National =
Body?</STRONG><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <BR>There is some confusion about who these folks are and the =
interests=20
        they represent.&nbsp; Here's a scorecard for those playing along =
at=20
        home.</LI></OL>
      <H3><A name=3D2.0h>2</A>. The US Score So Far</H3>
      <P><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/jasonmatusow/archive/2008/03/14/united-stat=
es-votes-to-approve-open-xml.aspx">United=20
      States Votes to Approve Open XML</A>.&nbsp; Jason Matusow reports =
that the=20
      US National Body has concluded a letter ballot that basically =
affirms its=20
      original approval of DIS 29500 in the September, 2007, ISO/IEC =
JTC1=20
      balloting.&nbsp; This is the official result.&nbsp; There will be =
a=20
      resolution meeting for this, but I don't think there is any =
expectation=20
      that the outcome will change.</P>
      <P>As Matusow points out, <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Dvote&amp;com=
mittee=3DINCITS&amp;ballot_id=3D2558&amp;_UserReference=3D459CB1A6A3740BD=
247DA9FDC">the=20
      vote for approval</A> is 11-4-1 (yes-no-abstain) with one "<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118952">not=20
      yet voted</A>" (perhaps like voting "present"?).&nbsp; Either way, =
the 11=20
      affirmative votes ensure a 2/3 majority.</P>
      <P>Whatever adjustments are made, this is the US National Body =
Executive=20
      Board determination.</P>
      <UL>
        <LI><STRONG>This is different than the V1 technical committee=20
        recommendation</STRONG>.&nbsp;&nbsp; This is the response to a =
<A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/archive.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;bal=
lot_id=3D2558&amp;_UserReference=3DC1868611BE3AC38B47DC0486">letter=20
        ballot</A> that was conducted following the V1 technical =
committee=20
        recommendation.&nbsp; This is the Executive Board=20
        determination.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>The V1 technical committee recommended=20
        approval</STRONG>.&nbsp; There was a <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2008/03/07/us-v1-technical-=
committee-votes-to-recommend-approval-of-dis-29500.aspx">lengthy=20
        conference call</A> on Friday March 7, 2008, where the BRM =
outcome was=20
        discussed and the committee then voted to recommend to the =
Executive=20
        Board that the original approval of DIS 29500 be affirmed.&nbsp; =

        <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>The US Delegation to the Ballot Resolution Meeting =
voted=20
        "no" on some resolutions there</STRONG>.&nbsp; This was a small=20
        delegation led by&nbsp; Frank Farance.&nbsp; These were votes on =
editing=20
        of DIS 29500 and not on DIS 29500's approval or rejection at =
ISO/IEC=20
        JTC1.&nbsp; The most famous delegation "no" vote was a blanket =
vote on=20
        over 800 proposed responses (and although selected line-item =
voting was=20
        allowed, the US did not do that).<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; </LI></UL>
      <H3><A name=3D3.0h>3</A>. "Who Are Those Guys?"</H3>
      <P>In the United States, the promulgation of standards is =
accomplished by=20
      non-governmental bodies.&nbsp; There is a complex of such=20
      organizations.&nbsp; Keeping track of them is further complicated =
by the=20
      different ways they are associated with international activities, =
such as=20
      ISO/IEC JTC1 and other technical committees of ISO.</P>
      <P>The pinnacle US standards organization is ANSI, the <A=20
      href=3D"http://ansi.org/">American National Standards =
Institute</A>.&nbsp;=20
      ANSI accredits other organizations to develop standards.&nbsp; =
There are=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://publicaa.ansi.org/sites/apdl/Documents/Forms/AllItems.aspx=
?RootFolder=3D%2fsites%2fapdl%2fDocuments%2fStandards%20Activities%2fAmer=
ican%20National%20Standards%2fANSI%20Accredited%20Standards%20Developers"=
>over=20
      200 of those</A>.&nbsp; Some of them, such as Underwriters =
Laboratory, are=20
      audited designators, but most standards developers don't certify =
processes=20
      or products.&nbsp;&nbsp; My favorite, after tallying the current =
list, is=20
      the Hydrogen Executive Leadership Panel.&nbsp; (By the way, OASIS =
is not=20
      one of these, nor are the W3C and IETF.&nbsp; Ecma International =
is not a=20
      U.S. organization, of course.)</P>
      <P>INCITS, the <A href=3D"http://www.incits.org/">InterNational =
Committee=20
      for Information Technology Standards</A>, "is the primary U.S. =
focus of=20
      standardization in the field of Information and Communications=20
      Technologies (ICT), encompassing storage, processing, transfer, =
display,=20
      management, organization, and retrieval of information. As such, =
INCITS=20
      also serves as ANSI's Technical Advisory Group (TAG) for ISO/IEC =
Joint=20
      Technical Committee 1."&nbsp; With respect to ISO/IEC JTC1, INCITS =
is the=20
      US/TAG and acts as the US National Body in that capacity.&nbsp; It =
is the=20
      INCITS Executive Board that just held the letter ballot that =
affirms the=20
      US approval of DIS 29500.</P>
      <P>INCITS has a pot full of <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/stds/Main.taf?Method=3DPublic&amp;_functio=
n=3DcommList&amp;_UserReference=3D255BC1D9AC5D7CCB47DBF70B">technical=20
      committees</A> (and they may have their own subcommittees and =
working=20
      groups of various kinds).&nbsp; <A=20
      href=3D"http://v1.incits.org/v1htm/v1.htm">Technical Committee =
V1</A> is on=20
      Office and Publishing Systems.&nbsp; They are a Technical Advisory =
Group=20
      for ISO/IEC JTC1 SC34.&nbsp; We see similar mirroring in other =
National=20
      Bodies.&nbsp; The German DIN NIA 34 has a similar function.&nbsp; =
V1 was=20
      once a tiny little group.&nbsp; Now there are <A=20
      href=3D"http://v1.incits.org/v1mem.htm">22 members</A> and much is =
being=20
      said about that.&nbsp; Whatever the composition signifies, V1 has =
a <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.incits.org/whatsdue.htm#INCITS_V1">broader =
charge</A>=20
      than just dealing with DIS 29500:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Since the scope of V1 is quite broad, it is necessary to =
create=20
        closer liaisons with other technical committees and special =
groups in=20
        order to establish good relations to avoid duplication of =
efforts. A=20
        number of new or extended areas are gaining interest in V1 such =
as Voice=20
        Messaging, Icons, Data Architecture, Font Services, MHS/X.400,=20
        Publishing Applications, Models and others related to Office and =

        Publishing Systems."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>If you wonder where INCITS came from and how it operates, here =
is <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.incits.org/geninfo.htm">more context</A>:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"The InterNational Committee for Information Technology =
Standards=20
        (INCITS) is the forum of choice for information technology =
developers,=20
        producers and users for the creation and maintenance of formal=20
        <EM>de</EM> <EM>jure</EM> IT standards. INCITS is accredited by, =
and=20
        operates under rules approved by, the American National =
Standards=20
        Institute (ANSI). These rules are designed to ensure that =
voluntary=20
        standards are developed by the consensus of directly and =
materially=20
        affected interests.</P>
        <P>"INCITS is sponsored by the <A=20
        href=3D"http://www.itic.org/">Information Technology Industry =
Council=20
        (ITI)</A>, a trade association representing the leading U.S. =
providers=20
        of information technology products and services. ITI members =
employ more=20
        than one million people in the United States and in 2000, their =
revenues=20
        exceeded $668 billion worldwide. </P>
        <P>"INCITS was founded as Accredited Standards Committee X3 in =
1961. The=20
        last accreditation was <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.incits.org/Archive/2001/it010416/it010416.htm">April=20
        19, 2001</A> under the name INCITS."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>When I was last directly involved in these activities, around =
1970, it=20
      was still X3 and the technical committees had designations like =
X3.4.2,=20
      X3J3 and X3V1 (if there had been a V1 then).&nbsp; At that time, =
ITI was=20
      known as CBEMA, the Computers and Business Equipment Manufacturers =

      Association.</P>
      <P>In addition to standards development being carried out by=20
      non-governmental bodies in the United States, the US also operates =
under a=20
      <STRONG>voluntary</STRONG> standards regime.&nbsp; For the most =
part,=20
      there is no mandating of standards and no one, not even =
participants in=20
      standards development, are obligated to adhere to a standard just =
because=20
      it exists.&nbsp; </P>
      <P>Of course, adherence to specific standards can be required in=20
      procurement activities, and requirement of particular =
certification of=20
      standards-conformance might also be required.&nbsp; This is all=20
      pretty-much outside the purview of the standards developers in the =

      voluntary model.&nbsp; (Some standards are given regulatory force, =

      incorporated in building, electrical, food-processing, and other =
codes,=20
      but this is not under the authority of standards developers as =
standards=20
      developers in the ANSI regime.)</P>
      <P>Here's the reminder that appeared at the bottom of the =
just-conducted=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/archive.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;bal=
lot_id=3D2558&amp;_UserReference=3DC1868611BE3AC38B47DC0486">letter=20
      ballot</A>:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Voluntary Standards are developed with the intention and =
expectation=20
        that the standards will be suitable for wide application. As =
their use=20
        is likewise voluntary, an affirmative vote does not commit an=20
        organization or group represented on the committee to the use of =
the=20
        voluntary standard under consideration. If you find that you =
cannot vote=20
        YES and wish to vote NO or ABSTAIN, please state this and =
explain the=20
        reasons for your position in the places =
provided."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <H3><A name=3D4.0h>4</A>. Yes, But <EM>WHO</EM> Are Those =
Guys?</H3>
      <P>In January, there were <A =
href=3D"http://www.incits.org/ebmem.htm">19=20
      members</A> of the INCITS Executive Board, but <STRIKE>at this=20
      time</STRIKE> there are only 17 voting members <U>on this=20
      question</U>.&nbsp; Here is how they turned out for the letter =
ballot.</P>
      <H4><A name=3D4.1h>4.1</A> Not Voting</H4>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.aimglobal.org/">AIM Global</A> and <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.qualcomm.com/">Qualcomm, Inc.</A> did not =
return ballots=20
      and might not <U>(yet)</U> be =
<STRIKE>(</STRIKE>voting<STRIKE>)</STRIKE>=20
      members <STRIKE>any longer</STRIKE>.&nbsp;&nbsp; </P>
      <P>Intel returned a "not yet voted" ballot, as already =
reported.</P>
      <H4><A name=3D4.2h>4.2</A> Abstention</H4>
      <P>The <A href=3D"http://www.ieee.org/">IEEE</A> <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118943">abstained</A>.&nbsp;=20
      The IEEE, in addition to being a professional association, is also =
an=20
      accredited standards developer.&nbsp; </P>
      <H4><A name=3D4.3h>4.3</A> The Loyal Opposition</H4>
      <P>The four "No" votes are from <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118959">Adobe</A>,=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118948">Farance</A>,=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118944">IBM</A>=20
      (<A =
href=3D"http://www.incits.org/ref-docs/IBM-Comments_INCITS2558.pdf">PDF=20
      text</A>), and <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118949">Oracle</A>.</P>
      <P>Of these, <A href=3D"http://farance.com/">Farance</A> is not a =
household=20
      word.&nbsp; Farance, Incorporated, is a technology firm that is =
heavily=20
      engaged in the development of standards, with some current =
emphasis on=20
      metadata and learning technologies.&nbsp; Frank Farance was the =
Head of=20
      Delegation to the DIS 29500 Ballot Resolution Meeting.&nbsp; As =
part of=20
      the August, 2007, deliberations on a US response to the DIS 29500 =
ballot,=20
      Farance cast <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.incits.org/archive/2007/in071258/in071258.htm">this=20
      ballot</A> recommending conditional approval (that is, "No, with=20
      comments").</P>
      <P>A common theme is the impossibility of conducting adequate =
review of a=20
      6,000 page specification under the fast-track procedure.&nbsp; IBM =
and=20
      Oracle both refer to "procedural irregularities" with IBM =
recording an=20
      extensive challenge to the validity of the INCITS process.</P>
      <P>The Farance objection asserts that "A position of 'approval' is =

      completely unacceptable to us" so it is a procedural appeal too, I =

      suppose.&nbsp; The objection goes on to propose a remedy after =
enumerating=20
      the deficiencies.&nbsp; More about that below (section <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#5.0h">5</A>).</P>
      <H4><A name=3D4.4h>4.4</A> Friends Across the Aisle</H4>
      <P>Some of the "Yes" votes are from well-known organizations: <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118947">Apple</A>,=20
      <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118945">Hewlett=20
      Packard</A>, <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118956">Lexmark=20
      International</A>, <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118953">Microsoft</A>,=20
      and <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118953">Sony=20
      Electronics</A>.&nbsp; These five are not enough to carry the =
day.&nbsp;=20
      </P>
      <P>The remaining votes include three substantial organizations =
that are=20
      mostly unfamiliar to me:</P>
      <UL>
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118950">Electronic=20
        Industries Alliance</A> (the <A=20
        href=3D"http://www.eia.org/">EIA</A>).&nbsp; This is a major =
industry=20
        association and also an accredited standards developer (think =
EIA RS-232=20
        and RS-449).<BR>&nbsp;=20
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118954">EMC</A>,=20
        <A href=3D"http://www.emc.com/">self-identified</A> as "the =
world leader=20
        in information management and storage."&nbsp; EMC provides =
solutions for=20
        mainframe, IBM DB2, Microsoft, Oracle, and SAP.&nbsp; Documentum =
is now=20
        their product.&nbsp; Oh.&nbsp; I need to get out =
more.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118955">GS1=20
        US</A>, another non-profit accredited standards developer that =
focuses=20
        on <A href=3D"http://gs1us.org/">global supply-chain =
solutions</A>.&nbsp;=20
        If you need a Universal Product Code to stick on your product =
packages,=20
        you get it from GS1 US.</LI></UL>
      <P>The last three "yes" votes are of an entirely different =
breed:</P>
      <UL>
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118958">U.S.=20
        Department of Homeland Security</A>, with an expression of =
alignment=20
        with NIST and DoD<BR>&nbsp;=20
        <LI><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118957">U.S.=20
        Department of Defense</A>, after consultation with other Federal =

        agencies and expressing alignment with NIST<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI>U.S. <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://ballot.itic.org/itic/tallyvote.taf?function=3Ddetail&amp;r=
esponse_id=3D118946">National=20
        Institute for Science and Technology</A> (<A=20
        href=3D"http://www.nist.gov/">NIST</A>).&nbsp; This is a Federal =
agency=20
        under the U.S. Department of Commerce.&nbsp; Formerly know as =
the=20
        National Bureau of Standards, NIST is <EM><U>not</U></EM> in =
charge of=20
        standardization in the United States.&nbsp; NIST/ITL (the <A=20
        href=3D"http://www.itl.nist.gov/">Information Technology =
Laboratory</A>)=20
        is an accredited standards developer, however.&nbsp; NIST has, =
in the=20
        past, drafted Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) =
that apply=20
        to agencies of the U.S. Federal Government.&nbsp; These are =
often=20
        existing public standards adapted for governmental use.&nbsp; =
There is=20
        an extensive report on NIST participation in INCITS with respect =
to ODF,=20
        OOXML, and the DIS 29500 process (<A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.itl.nist.gov/March%2014%20Updated%20NIST%20FAQ.pdf">PD=
F=20
        text</A>).&nbsp; There is also a <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.nist.gov/public_affairs/techbeat/tbx2008_0314_ooxml.ht=
m">NIST=20
        press release</A> on the matter.</LI></UL>
      <H3><A name=3D5.0h>5</A>. Eagerly-Anticipated Maintenance?</H3>
      <P>I'm intrigued by the following statement in the NIST =
ballot:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"With respect to the 'Additional INCITS/V1 Recommendations =
Not=20
        Related to this Vote,' included in INCITS Letter Ballot 2558, =
NIST=20
        interprets these recommendations to be that the USNB should =
support one=20
        of the following options: </P>
        <P>"1) Should DIS 29500 fail to achieve the criteria for =
approval as an=20
        ISO/IEC standard, DIS 29500, as modified by the BRM, should be =
submitted=20
        to JTC 1/SC 34 for fast processing, via the JTC 1 combined NP =
[New Work=20
        Item Proposal] and CD [Committee Draft] ballots process, and =
progressed=20
        under the JTC 1 accelerated time frame. </P>
        <P>"2) Should DIS 29500, as modified by the BRM, achieve the =
criteria=20
        for approval as an ISO/IEC standard, to correct remaining issues =
from=20
        the BRM, SC 34 should approve an NP for a revision of IS 29500 =
using the=20
        JTC 1 5-stage process under the accelerated time =
frame."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>No "Additional INCITS/V1 Recommendations" appear as part of the =
ballot=20
      form.&nbsp; There is something about them in the Farance ballot=20
though:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>"Although we disapprove of the DIS 29500 at its present =
state,=20
        Farance Inc. is supportive of the 29500 technologies becoming an =
ISO/IEC=20
        standard. We want the work done right and done quickly to =
address=20
        industry and international needs. Farance Inc. has proposed in =
INCITS/V1=20
        two New Work Item Proposals [NPs] for SC34: one NP if DIS 29500 =
succeeds=20
        and a different NP if DIS 29500 fails. These NP proposals were=20
        acknowledged in the INCITS EB ballot wording. We hope these NPs =
will be=20
        a starting point to trying to fix/finish issues within the 29500 =
text,=20
        and we hope these immediate needs can be addressed over the next =
9-14=20
        months."&nbsp; </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>It is not clear that NIST is throwing its support behind that =
idea or=20
      is simply clarifying its understanding.&nbsp; <STRIKE>I have =
failed to=20
      find the particular JTC1 procedures that are referred to as "the =
JTC1=20
      5-stage process under the accelerated time frame."&nbsp; I'm still =

      looking.</STRIKE></P>
      <TABLE cellSpacing=3D2 cellPadding=3D4 width=3D800 border=3D1>
        <TBODY>
        <TR>
          <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D794>
            <P><STRONG>[Update:</STRONG> There are three different =
schedule=20
            templates for JTC1 New Work Item Proposals: accelerated (24 =
months=20
            to published standard), default (36 months), and extended =
(48=20
            months) on the lines of [<A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#1h">1</A>:=20
            <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://isotc.iso.org/livelink/livelink/fetch/2000/2489/Ittf_Home/=
Directives/Chapter6.html#6.3">section=20
            6.3</A>]:</P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D2 cellPadding=3D2 width=3D"90%" =
align=3Dcenter=20
border=3D2>
              <TBODY>
              <TR>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D175>
                  <P align=3Dright><EM>Schedule</EM></P></TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D147>
                  <P align=3Dcenter><EM>Committee Draft =
(CD)</EM></P></TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D130><EM>Approval Draft =
(DIS)</EM></TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D125><EM>Published =
Standard</EM></TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D208>
                  <P align=3Dright><STRONG>Accelerated</STRONG></P></TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D167>none</TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D144>6 months (enquiry =
draft)</TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D136>24 months</TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D218>
                  <P align=3Dright><STRONG>Default</STRONG></P></TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D174>12 months</TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D149>30 months</TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D140>36 months</TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D219>
                  <P align=3Dright><STRONG>Extended</STRONG></P></TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D177>12 months</TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D151>43 months</TD>
                <TD vAlign=3Dtop width=3D142>48 =
months</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P>The entire section on Programme of Work is important for =
an=20
            understanding of the process [<A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#1h">1</A>:=20
            <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://isotc.iso.org/livelink/livelink/fetch/2000/2489/Ittf_Home/=
Directives/Chapter6.html">section=20
            6</A>].</P>
            <P>The JTC1 5-stage procedure has 6 stages (0 to 5), [<A=20
            =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/03/nfoware-tracking-o=
oxml-dis-29500-into.asp#1h">1</A>:=20
            <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://isotc.iso.org/livelink/livelink/fetch/2000/2489/Ittf_Home/=
Directives/Chapter12.html#12.1">section=20
            12.1</A>]:</P>
            <OL start=3D0>
              <LI><STRONG>Preliminary:</STRONG> A study period is =
underway=20
              [probably brief for OOXML]<BR>&nbsp;=20
              <LI><STRONG>Proposal Stage:</STRONG> the NP is under =
consideration=20
              (requires balloting and formulation of the work, assurance =
of=20
              participation, and other important formalities, [could be =
brief=20
              for post-IS 29500, might be contentious=20
              otherwise])<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
              <LI><STRONG>Preparatory Stage:</STRONG> Working Draft (WD) =
under=20
              consideration [probably using either IS 29500 or updated =
ECMA-376=20
              as initial WD]<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
              <LI><STRONG>Committee Stage:</STRONG> A Committee Draft is =
under=20
              consideration [something tells me there will need to be =
something=20
              like that either way, using normal =
processes]<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
              <LI><STRONG>Approval Stage:</STRONG> An FDIS is under=20
              consideration [more-or-less where the Fast-Track DIS 29500 =
process=20
              started and where DIS 29500 is right now]<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
              <LI><STRONG>Publication Stage:</STRONG> An IS is being =
prepared=20
              for publication [a process yet to be completed if DIS =
29500 is=20
              approved]</LI></OL>
            <P>My personal reality check suggests that the odds of this =
getting=20
            off on the right foot (starting work around =
September-October 2008)=20
            is if there is a&nbsp; published IS 29500 as a concrete =
starting=20
            point.&nbsp;&nbsp; Whatever process is put in place, there =
must be=20
            room for feedback from implementation experience and any =
working=20
            agreements that are formulated as part of document =
interoperability=20
            efforts.&nbsp; Putting the necessary technical muscle into =
an SC34=20
            working group and coordinating with NB counterparts (such as =

            INCITS/V1 and others) will be daunting and =
time-consuming.&nbsp;=20
            Some way of providing intermediate guidance and =
(provisional)=20
            interpretations may also be important.&nbsp; I'm not betting =
on the=20
            accelerated timeframe even under the best of =
conditions.]&nbsp;=20
          </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
      <P>Here's what I <U>still</U> think.&nbsp; OOXML is the new =
COBOL.&nbsp;=20
      Really.&nbsp; That's a good thing (with a 40-year life span, for=20
      starters), if the energy and pace can be achieved with the =
requisite=20
      quality and care.</P>
      <HR>
